mca-1 encodes one of three C. elegans plasma membrane Ca2+ ATPases (PMCAs); by homology, MCA-1 is predicted to function as a molecular pump that couples ATP hydrolysis to extrusion of cytosolic Ca2+; when expressed in insect cells, MCA-1 exhibits calcium-pumping ATPase activity and binding to human calmodulin; large-scale RNAi screens indicate that mca-1 activity is required for normal coordinated locomotion and rates of growth; an mca-1::gfp reporter fusion is expressed solely in the excretory canal.
ZK1251.3 is an ortholog of human SRD5A1 (steroid 5 alpha-reductase 1); ZK1251.3 is predicted to have 3-oxo-5-alpha-steroid 4-dehydrogenase activity, based on protein domain information.

cka-1 encodes an isoform of choline kinase whose activity has been verified in vitro, and that has a strong preference for choline over ethanolamine; CKA-1 and CKA-2 comprise a related group ('A') of choline kinases.

fat-4 encodes a delta-5 fatty acid desaturase; when expressed heterologously in S. cerevisiae, FAT-4 converts di-homo-gamma-linolenic acid (20:3delta8,11,14) to arachidonic acid (20:4delta5,8,11,14), an important precursor in eicosanoid metabolism, as well as on other fatty acids (C18 to C20); FAT-4 is is required in vivo for delta-5 unsaturated fatty acid synthesis.

fat-3 encodes a delta-6 fatty acid desaturase ('linoleoyl-CoA desaturase') containing an N-terminal cytochrome b5 domain that is orthologous to the vertebrate fatty acid desaturases (FADS); FAT-3 expressed in yeast uses linoleic and alpha-linolenic acid as substrates; FAT-3 is absolutely required in vivo for synthesis of delta-6 fatty acids, and also required for fully normal synthesis of C20 fatty acids; FAT-3 is required for a normally fast growth rate and movement speed, and for normal defecation rhythms and fertility; fat-3 is also required for regulation of basal innate immunity.
mccc-1 encodes an ortholog of the human gene ALPHA METHYLCROTONOYL-COENZYME A CARBOXYLASE 1 (MCCC1; 3-MCC), which when mutated leads to beta-methylcrotonyl-glycinuria (OMIM:210200).

srs-2 encodes a predicted cytoplasmic seryl-tRNA synthetase (SerRS), a class II aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that catalyzes the attachment of serine to its cognate tRNA and is thus required for protein biosynthesis; in C. elegans, SRS-2 activity is required for embryonic and germline development and normal postembryonic growth rates.

pyp-1 encodes, by alternative splicing, three isoforms of an inorganic  pyrophosphatase required for embryonic and larval viability, intestinal  function, and distal tip cell migration; PYP-1 is catalytically active  in vitro, and is expressed in neurons, intestine, and coelomocytes;  PYP-1 is orthologous to Drosophila NURF-38, and to human PPA1  (OMIM:179030) and PPA2; by orthology with NURF-38, PYP-1 is also  predicted to participate in nucleosome remodelling.
The dhp-2 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene DIHYDROPYRIMIDINASE (DPYS), which when mutated leads to dihydropyrimidinuria (OMIM:222748).
dhs-31 is expressed in the hypodermis and the vulva.

pld-1 encodes the C. elegans ortholog of phospholipase D; by homology, PLD-1 is predicted to hydrolyze phosphatidylcholine (PC) to phosphatidic acid (PA) and choline; loss of pld-1 activity via RNAi reveals that pld-1 may play a role in phagosome maturation; large-scale expression studies indicate that pld-1 is widely expressed in larvae and adults, and seen in the pharynx, intestine, nervous system, body wall muscle, and hypodermis.

gcy-29 is an ortholog of human NPR1 (natriuretic peptide receptor 1) and NPR2 (natriuretic peptide receptor 2); gcy-29 is predicted to have phosphorus-oxygen lyase activity, based on protein domain information; gcy-29 is expressed in certain interneurons and certain amphid neurons.
gst-2 is an ortholog of members of the human GST (Soluble glutathione S-transferases) family including HPGDS; gst-2 is expressed in the head.

gst-4 encodes a putative glutathione-requiring prostaglandin D synthase; gst-4 is required for sperm to normally migrate towards a PUFA-based signal exuded by oocytes; gst-4(RNAi) hermaphrodites are infertile, both through aberrant loss of their own sperm and through failure of males to effectively inseminate them; in mammalian eicosanoid signalling, prostaglandin D synthase is required for the conversion of prostaglandin H2 into D2; gst-4 mRNA is expressed in adults, and accumulation increases in response to paraquat.
dhs-12 encodes a predicted short-chain dehydrogenase.
gst-3 encodes a predicted glutathione S-transferase.

Category 3: Neuronal function: synaptic function: neurotransmitter metabolism
Description: The gta-1 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene GABAT, which when mutated leads to GABA-transaminase deficiency (OMIM:137150).

qns-1 encodes an NAD+ synthase orthologous to human NAD synthetase 1 (HGNC:NADSYN1); by homology, QNS-1 is predicted to catalyze the final step in NAD+ synthesis; loss of qns-1 activity via RNAi results in reduced NAD+ levels and shortened adult lifespan.
tkt-1 encodes an ortholog of the human gene TRANSKETOLASE (TKT; OMIM:606781), which when mutated leads to Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome (OMIM:277730).

ech-8 is an ortholog of human EHHADH (enoyl-CoA hydratase and 3-hydroxyacyl CoA dehydrogenase); ech-8 is predicted to have 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity, based on protein domain information.

ech-9 is an ortholog of human EHHADH (enoyl-CoA hydratase and 3-hydroxyacyl CoA dehydrogenase); ech-9 is predicted to have 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity, based on protein domain information.
lipl-7 is an ortholog of members of the human Lipases family including LIPF; lipl-7 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, acting on ester bonds, based on protein domain information.
thk-1 is an ortholog of human TK1 (thymidine kinase 1); thk-1 is predicted to have ATP binding activity, based on protein domain information.
acs-18 is an ortholog of human ACSL1 (acyl-CoA synthetase long-chain family member 1); acs-18 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-59 is an ortholog of members of the human UGT (UDP glucuronosyltransferases) family including UGT8; ugt-59 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
sir-2.1 encodes an NAD-dependent protein deacetylase with similarity to Saccharomyces cerevisiae Sir2p and mammalian SIRT1.
pges-2 is an ortholog of human PTGES2 (prostaglandin E synthase 2); pges-2 is expressed in the muscle cell, hypodermis, tail, intestinal cell, ventral nerve cord, and the head neurons.

irs-1 encodes a predicted cytoplasmic isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase (IleRS), an aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that catalyzes the attachment of isoleucine to its cognate tRNA and is thus required for protein biosynthesis; loss of irs-1 activity via RNA-mediated interference (RNAi) results in sterility, embryonic lethality, and slower rates of growth, indicating that IRS-1 is essential for development.

R10H10.6 is an ortholog of human RFK (riboflavin kinase); RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that R10H10.6 is affected by daf-2, daf-16, hsf-1, sir-2.1, ain-2, fbf-1, isp-1, and nuo-6; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that R10H10.6 is affected by Rotenone, Atrazine, Cadmium, Humic substances, and Paraquat; tiling array, RNA sequencing, and microarray studies indicate that R10H10.6 is enriched in the hypodermis, germ line, and intestine and in the PLM neurons.

RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that F13B12.4 is affected by Methylmercury hydroxide, Methylmercuric chloride, D-glucose, Resveratrol, Cadmium, Colistin, and adsorbable organic bromine compounds; tiling array and microarray studies indicate that F13B12.4 is enriched in the germline precursor cell and hypodermis and in neurons.

ugt-43 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-43 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-44 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-44 is involved in innate immune response; ugt-44 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that F01D4.8 is affected by Multi-walled carbon nanotubes, D-glucose, Quercetin, Humic substances, single-walled carbon nanotubes, Colistin, Sirolimus, and Octopamine; tiling array and microarray studies indicate that F01D4.8 is enriched in the hermaphrodite-specific tissues and in the dopaminergic and FLP neurons.

nkb-2 is an ortholog of human ATP1B3 (ATPase Na+/K+ transporting subunit beta 3), ATP4B (ATPase H+/K+ transporting beta subunit) and members of the ATP1 (ATPase Na+/K+ transporting subunits) family including ATP1B1; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that nkb-2 is affected by Ethanol, Nicotinic acid, Methylmercuric chloride, Rotenone, Manganese chloride, D-glucose, Resveratrol, Humic substances, single-walled carbon nanotubes, Paraquat, Colistin, and adsorbable organic bromine compounds; RNA sequencing studies indicate that nkb-2 is enriched in the germ line and male.
R09H10.3 is orthologous to the human gene TRANSTHYRETIN (PREALBUMIN, AMYLOIDOSIS TYPE I) (TTR; OMIM:176300), which when mutated leads to disease.
fmo-1 encodes a flavin-containing monoxygenase homologous to human FMO1, FMO2, and FMO3 (OMIM:602079, mutated in trimethylaminuria).
fmo-2 encodes a flavin-containing monoxygenase homologous to human FMO1, FMO2, and FMO3 (OMIM:602079, mutated in trimethylaminuria).
R102.4 is predicted to have lyase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-54 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-54 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
inpp-1 is an ortholog of members of the human Phosphoinositide phosphatases family including INPP5E; inpp-1 is expressed in the nervous system; inpp-1 is localized to the cytoplasm.

hars-1 encodes the sole histidyl-tRNA synthetase (HisRS), class II aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases that catalyze the attachment of histidine to its cognate tRNAs and are thus required for protein biosynthesis; in C. elegans, hars-1 is required for larval and germline development, and hence normal fertility; hars-1(RNAi) animals exhibit a reduced numbers of functional germ cells which is partially suppressed by ced-4 mutations, and a hars-1 loss-of-function mutation exhibits arrest at the L2 larval stage of development; mutations in human HARS2 cause Perrault syndrome, which is characterized by female ovarian dysgenesis and sensorineural hearing loss in both females and males.
pyk-2 encodes one of two C. elegans pyruvate kinases; large-scale expression studies show that pyk-2 is expressed in the larval and adult intestine.
The ndx-9 gene encodes a member of the NADH pyrophosphatase subfamily of the NUDIX hydrolases.
mogs-1 encodes a mannosyl-oligosaccharide glucosidase (E.C. 3.2.1.106) orthologous to the human gene A-GLUCOSIDASE I (GCS1; OMIM:601336), which when mutated leads to disease.

F13H10.5 is an ortholog of human ENPP7 (ectonucleotide pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase 7) and ENPP5 (ectonucleotide pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase 5 (putative)); F13H10.5 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information.

hrg-4 encodes a transmembrane protein that is conserved amongst nematodes; hrg-4 functions to mediate heme homeostasis, likely by regulating heme transport across the plasma membrane; in vitro, HRG-4 exhibits heme binding over a broad pH range and when expressed in Xenopus oocytes, can stimulate heme-dependent currents; when expressed in HEK293 cells, HRG-4 localizes primarily to the plasma membrane; hrg-4 mRNA expression is significantly upregulated in response to heme deficiency.
alh-3 encodes an aldehyde dehydrogenase predicted to be mitochondrial.
ard-1 encodes a homolog of mammalian 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase (HADH II)/amyloid-beta binding alcohol dehydrogenase (ABAD) that is predicted to be mitochondrial.

F01G4.5 is an ortholog of human PIGQ (phosphatidylinositol glycan anchor biosynthesis class Q); F01G4.5 is predicted to have phosphatidylinositol N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase activity, based on protein domain information; F01G4.5 is localized to the endoplasmic reticulum.

mboa-4 encodes a putative transmembrane O-acyl transferase (MBOAT)  orthologous to human MBOAT1 (OMIM:611732), and paralogous to C54G7.2 and  ZK550.1; MBOA-4 has no obvious function in mass RNAi assays, and  mboa-4(RNAi) animals incorporate exogenous arachidonic acid into  phosphatidylcholine (PC), phosphatidylserine (PS) and  phosphatidylethanolamine (PE) normally.
cpt-2 encodes a carnitine palmitoyltranferase orthologous to the human gene CPT2, an enzyme involved in fatty acid oxidation.

R07H5.8 is an ortholog of human ADK (adenosine kinase); R07H5.8 is predicted to have adenosine kinase activity, based on protein domain information; R07H5.8 is expressed in the pharynx, hypodermis, reproductive system, intestine, excretory cell, and the body wall musculature.

B0035.3 is an ortholog of human MACROD2 (MACRO domain containing 2) and MACROD1 (MACRO domain containing 1); microarray, tiling array, proteomic, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that B0035.3 is affected by cgh-1, cyc-1, daf-12, gld-1, let-7, tatn-1, clk-1, npr-1, jmjd-3.1, hsf-1, flp-6, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, emb-4, sir-2.1, and fbf-1; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that B0035.3 is affected by Rotenone, Manganese chloride, Resveratrol, Atrazine, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, and Sirolimus; tiling array, RNA sequencing, and microarray studies indicate that B0035.3 is enriched in the germline precursor cell, germ line, and intestine.
gspd-1 encodes a protein orthologous to human GLUCOSE-6-PHOSPHATE DEHYDROGENASE (G6PD; OMIM:305900), which when mutated leads to disease.

cyp-31A2 encodes a class 4 cytochrome P450 predicted to hydroxylate polyunsaturated fats (PUFAs); CYP-31A2 is required for sperm to normally migrate towards a PUFA-based signal exuded by oocytes; cyp-31A2(RNAi) hermaphrodites are infertile, both through aberrant loss of their own sperm and through failure of males to effectively inseminate them; in mammalian eicosanoid signalling, class 4 cytochrome P450 is required for the omega hydroxylation of PUFAs, prostaglandins, and leukotrienes.

gfat-2 encodes a glucosamine--fructose-6-phosphate aminotransferase (EC:2.6.1.16, also known as glutamine-fructose-6-phosphate transaminase), paralogous to GFAT-1; GFAT-2 is predicted to catalyze the first, and rate-limiting, step of the hexosamine pathway in which glucosamine-6-phosphate is synthesized from L-glutamine and fructose-6-phosphate and ultimately converted to UDP-N-acetylglucosamine (UDP-GlcNAc); gfat-2 transcripts are enriched during oogenesis; gfat-2(RNAi) animals have an osmotically-sensitive embryonic lethal phenotype, presumably because of defects in chitin and eggshell synthesis.

sms-1 is an ortholog of human SGMS2 (sphingomyelin synthase 2); sms-1 is expressed in the spermatheca, pharyngeal muscle cell, coelomocyte, pharyngeal gland cell, rectal muscle, body wall musculature, vulval muscle, and the ventral nerve cord.

The rib-1 gene encodes an ortholog of human EXT1; the family of EXT genes have GlcNAc transferase activities and are involved in the synthesis of heparin sulfate proteoglycans; the RIB-1 protein interacts with RIB-2 and coexpression of RIB-1 and RIB-2 proteins in vitro results in glycosyltransferase and heparin sulphate polymerase activities; rib-1 is also required for proper embryonic development, suggesting that rib-1 and rib-2 are required for the biosynthesis of glycosaminoglycans during development.
F12F6.7 is an ortholog of human POLD2 (DNA polymerase delta 2, accessory subunit); F12F6.7 is predicted to have DNA binding activity, based on protein domain information.

mars-1 encodes a predicted cytoplasmic methionyl-tRNA synthetase (MetRS), a class I aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that catalyzes the attachment of methionine to its cognate tRNA and is thus required for protein biosynthesis; MARS-1 is essential for embryogenesis and required also for a normal rate of postembryonic growth.

acl-3 encodes a glycerol-3-phosphate acyltransferase that is orthologous to human tafazzin (TAZ; OMIM:300394, mutated in Barth syndrome); by homology, ACL-3 is predicted to be a mitochondrial protein that plays a role in triacylglycerol metabolism; acl-3 expression shows some degree of dauer-specific induction.

ZK809.3 is an ortholog of human XRCC5 (X-ray repair cross complementing 5); microarray, proteomic, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that ZK809.3 is affected by clk-1, cyc-1, gld-1, let-7, emr-1, lem-2, jmjd-3.1, jmjd-1.2, sir-2.1, tdp-1, and let-60; microarray studies indicate that ZK809.3 is affected by Estrogen, Progesterone, and Sirolimus; proteomic and RNA sequencing studies indicate that ZK809.3 is enriched in the germ line and in the NSM neurons.
ZK792.1 is an ortholog of human PXYLP1 (2-phosphoxylose phosphatase 1); ZK792.1 is expressed in the nervous system, intestine, and the rectal epithelium.
ech-2 encodes an enoyl-coenzyme A hydratase, an enzyme involved in mitochondrial beta-oxidation of fatty acids.

fat-6 encodes an Acyl-CoA desaturase (also known as delta-9 fatty acid desaturase); when expressed heterologously in S. cerevisiae, FAT-6 rescues the fatty acid auxotrophy of the ole1 delta-9 desaturase mutant; FAT-6 readily desaturates stearic acid (18:0), or similar fatty acids (17:0 or 18:1 delta-11 trans), but shows less activity on palmitic acid (16:0), and no activity on other medium chain fatty acids (14:0 or 15:0); based on similarity to mammalian Acyl-CoA desaturases, FAT-6 is predicted to localize to the endoplasmic reticulum membrane.
tgt-1 encodes a tRNA-guanine transglycosylase predicted to be mitochondrial.

phy-2 encodes  a catalytic alpha subunit of  collagen prolyl 4-hydroxylase (P4H) orthologous to human P4H alpha (II) isoform (OMIM: 600608); phy-2 is responsible for hydroxylation of cuticle collagen; loss-of-function mutations result in phenotypically wild-type animals, however phy-1; phy-2 double mutants arrest as embryos and larvae, suggesting that the PHY-1 and PHY-2 P2H alpha subunits function redundantly during development; phy-2 in complex with phy-1 is essential for the survival of the C. elegans; PHY-2, are expressed in the cuticle collagen-synthesizing hypodermal cells in a cyclical fashion that corresponds the moulting cycle and the times of maximal cuticle collagen synthesis; phy-2 is also expressed excretory cell, and spermatheca.

tag-335 is an ortholog of human GMPPB (GDP-mannose pyrophosphorylase B); tag-335 is predicted to have nucleotidyltransferase activity, based on protein domain information; tag-335 is expressed in the hypodermis.

ltah-1.1 is an ortholog of members of the human M1 metallopeptidases family including C9orf3; ltah-1.1 is involved in leukotriene biosynthetic process and peptide catabolic process; ltah-1.1 exhibits aminopeptidase activity and leukotriene-A4 hydrolase activity and is predicted to have metallopeptidase activity and zinc ion binding activity, based on protein domain information; ltah-1.1 is localized to the cytosol.

acs-20 encodes a protein homologous to the mammalian FATP1 and FATP4 fatty acid transport  proteins (FATP)/very long chain fatty acid acyl-CoA synthetases; acs-20 activity is required for proper cuticle development, specifically formation of a cuticle surface barrier that prevents penetration of small molecules; acs-20 may affect cuticle development via its role in incorporation of very long chain fatty acids, but not other fatty acids, into sphingomyelin; acs-20; acs-22 doubly mutant animals have more severe cuticle barrier defects than acs-20 single mutants, suggesting that the two genes function redundantly; acs-20 defects can be rescued by human Fatp4; an ACS-20::GFP fusion protein is expressed in the hyp7 and seam hypodermis, as well as the vulval and anal muscles; in hypodermal cells, ACS-20 localizes in a reticular pattern suggestive of localization to the endoplasmic reticulum.

dpm-3 encodes a putative regulatory subunit of dolichol phosphate  mannosyltransferase, orthologous to human DPM3 (OMIM:605951); in mass  RNAi assays, DPM-3 is required for normal body size, fertility, and  health.
acl-13 is an ortholog of human LPGAT1 (lysophosphatidylglycerol acyltransferase 1); acl-13 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring acyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-65 is an ortholog of members of the human UGT (UDP glucuronosyltransferases) family including UGT8; ugt-65 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
ipmk-1 is an ortholog of human IPMK (inositol polyphosphate multikinase); ipmk-1 is predicted to have kinase activity, based on protein domain information.

pgp-1 encodes a transmembrane protein that is a member of the P-glycoprotein subclass of the ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporter superfamily; along with PGP-3, PGP-1 is required for defense against the pathogenic Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14, and may facilitate ATP-dependent efflux of the toxic phenazine compounds produced by the bacteria; PGP-1 is expressed in the apical membrane of intestinal cells and in the intestinal valve cells.

vha-7 encodes an ortholog of subunit a of the membrane-bound (V0) domain of vacuolar proton-translocating ATPase (V-ATPase); VHA-7 is orthologous to human ATP6N1A (OMIM:192130), ATP6V0A2, ATP6V0A4 (OMIM:605239, mutated in distal renal tubular acidosis), and TCIRG1 (OMIM:604592, mutated in osteopetrosis); vha-7 is expressed in hypodermis and uterus; VHA-7 is dispensable for viability, since vha-7(RNAi) animals develop to normal, healthy adults; in S. cerevisiae, different V0 a-subunits (Stv1p and Vph1p) direct the assembly of V-ATPases to different membranes and organelles, suggesting that the profusion of such subunits in C. elegans (co-orthologous VHA-5, VHA-6, VHA-7, and six UNC-32 isoforms) may have a similar function; VHA-7 is predicted to capture protons from V-ATPase transmembrane rotor components and export the protons across the membrane.

Category 3: Signaling: heteromeric G protein: guanylyl cyclase
Description: gcy-18 encodes a receptor-type guanylyl cyclase that, along with gcy-8 and gcy-23, constitutes a subfamily of guanylyl cyclase genes in C. elegans; gcy-18 functions redundantly with gcy-8 and gcy-23, and upstream of tax-4, to regulate thermotaxis via the AFD thermosensory neurons, although of the three guanylyl cyclases required, genetic analyses suggest that GCY-18 is the primary guanylyl cyclase required; in addition, microarray experiments indicate that gcy-18 expression is induced in daf-16(RNAi); daf-2(RNAi) double mutants and repressed in daf-2(RNAi) mutants, suggesting that GCY-18 activity may contribute to a shortened lifespan; consistent with this, loss of gcy-18 activity via RNAi does result in lifespan extension; GCY-18 is expressed exclusively in the AFD thermosensory neurons, where it localizes to sensory endings.

fat-2 encodes a delta-12 fatty acyl desaturase that increases membrane fluidity when expressed in yeast, and that may protect against cold stress; FAT-2's substrate is unknown, but may be acyl-CoA; FAT-2 is required in vivo for normal levels of C18 or C20 polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs); FAT-2 is fully required for a sperm-attracting cue (perhaps an eicosanoid) secreted by oocytes, and partially required for the polarizing activity of PAR-3, PAR-6, and other proteins; FAT-2 is also required for a normally fast growth rate and movement rate, and for normal body shape, defecation rhythm, and brood size; when expressed in yeast, FAT-2 exhibits a v+3 mode of desaturase activity, catalyzing double bond formation three carbons from an existing double bond.
seld-1 is an ortholog of human SEPHS2 (selenophosphate synthetase 2) and SEPHS1 (selenophosphate synthetase 1); seld-1 is predicted to have ATP binding activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-22 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-22 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

gly-10 is an ortholog of human GALNT10 (polypeptide N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase 10) and GALNTL6 (polypeptide N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase-like 6); RNA sequencing, proteomic, and microarray studies indicate that gly-10 is affected by tatn-1, lin-28, glp-1, alg-1, emb-4, sir-2.1, ain-2, fbf-1, gld-2, and rnp-8; microarray studies indicate that gly-10 is affected by Cry5B, Paraquat, and Sirolimus; RNA sequencing studies indicate that gly-10 is enriched in the germ line.

Y45F10D.4 encodes a putative iron-sulfur cluster assembly enzyme that is  required for embryonic and larval viability, and that is orthologous to  human NIFUN and budding yeast ISU1 and ISU2; Y45F10D.4 expression levels  are unusually stable, with relatively little variation between adults,  dauers, and L3 larvae, or between wild-type and daf-2(e1370ts) or  daf-16(m26) mutant adults; by orthology with yeast ISU1, Y45F10D.4 is  predicted to bind FRH-1.
B0513.5 is an ortholog of human PRODH (proline dehydrogenase 1); B0513.5 is predicted to have proline dehydrogenase activity, based on protein domain information.
F52B11.2 is orthologous to the human gene PHOSPHOMANNOMUTASE 2 (PMS2; OMIM:601785), which when mutated leads to congenital disorder of glycosylation, type Ia.
The F55B11.1 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene XANTHINE DEHYDROGENASE (XDH), which when mutated leads to xanthinuria (OMIM:278300).
LLC1.3 is orthologous to the human gene DIHYDROLIPOAMIDE DEHYDROGENASE (DLD; OMIM:246900), which when mutated leads to dihydrolipoamide dehydrogenase deficiency.

coq-3 encodes a putative 3,4-dihydroxy-5-hexaprenylbenzoate methyltransferase, orthologous to S. cerevisiae COQ3; by orthology, COQ-3 is predicted to be in a complex with COQ-4 (and perhaps COQ-6), and to be required for two different steps of ubiquinone synthesis; COQ-3 is required for viability, ubiquinone (coenzyme Q9) biosynthesis and for normally short lifespan; coq-3 null mutations are lethal; coq-3(RNAi) animals have reduced levels of coenzyme Q9 and superoxide, and have abnormally long lifespans.

The nuo-3 locus encodes two distinct, non-overlapping proteins: Y57G11C.12a (homologous to human C3orf10/BRICK1, a component of the WAVE1 complex) and Y57G11C.12b (a putative NADH-ubiquinone oxidoreductase alpha subunit, homologous to human NDUFA6 [OMIM:602138]).
qars-1 encodes a glutaminyl (Q) tRNA synthetase that affects growth and embryonic and larval viability in large-scale RNAi screens; it is predicted to be mitochondrial.

Y7A9A.1 is an ortholog of human GGT5 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 5), GGT2 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 2) and GGT1 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 1); Y7A9A.1 is predicted to have glutathione hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information.

RNA sequencing studies indicate that mboa-5 is affected by tatn-1, npr-1, rbr-2, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, and smg-2; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that mboa-5 is affected by Multi-walled carbon nanotubes and Dafa#1; RNA sequencing studies indicate that mboa-5 is enriched in the male.
ZK550.5 is an ortholog of human PHYH (phytanoyl-CoA 2-hydroxylase); ZK550.5 is expressed in the nerve ring.
The ZK550.6 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene PHYTANOYL-COA HYDROXYLASE (PHYH; PAHX; OMIM:602026), which when mutated leads to Refsum disease (OMIM:266500).
gln-5 is an ortholog of human GLUL (glutamate-ammonia ligase); gln-5 is predicted to have glutamate-ammonia ligase activity, based on protein domain information.
T28F3.5 is an ortholog of human ACACB (acetyl-CoA carboxylase beta); T28F3.5 is predicted to have ATP binding activity and acetyl-CoA carboxylase activity, based on protein domain information.

C30H6.7 encodes a dihydrolipoamide acetyltransferase that is the second enzyme (E2) of the mitochondrial pyruvate dehydrogenase complex; by homology, the product of C30H6.7 is predicted to function in the transfer of an acetyl group to coenzyme A to generate acetyl-CoA for the citric acid cycle.

Microarray, proteomic, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that C30H6.8 is affected by cyc-1, spe-44, gld-1, let-7, tatn-1, prg-1, clk-1, hsf-1, mir-34, dpy-21, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, emb-4, and sir-2.1; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that C30H6.8 is affected by Rotenone, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, and Humic substances; tiling array, RNA sequencing, and microarray studies indicate that C30H6.8 is enriched in the germline precursor cell, germ line, and intestine and in the NSM neurons.
gab-3 is homologous to to the human gene GLUCOCEREBROSIDASE (GBA; OMIM:606463), which when mutated leads to Gaucher disease.

elo-2 encodes a palmitic acid elongase, homologous to polyunsaturated fatty acid (PUFA) elongases such as ELO-1, that is required for normally rapid growth, normally large body size, fertility, and for the quantitative regulation of the ultradian defecation rhythm; the joint action of ELO-2 with ELO-1 is strongly required for 20-carbon PUFA production and for general viability; loss of el-2 activity via RNAi also results in decreased intestinal dipeptide transport and increased fat droplet size; elo-2 is most strongly expressed in intestinal cells, as well as other tissues such as the ventral nerve cord, pharyngeal muscles, uterus, and tail.

egl-8 encodes a phospholipase C beta; egl-8 activity is required for pharyngeal pumping, defecation, activity levels, and innate immunity; egl-8 is genetically downstream of egl-30 with respect to aldicarb-induced paralysis, and is expressed in most or all neurons, with the strongest staining in the head and tail ganglia, and in the intestine.
lipl-5 encodes a lipase; lipl-5 is expressed in the intestine and its expression is negatively regulated in well-fed animals by MXL-3; lipl-5 expression is induced upon bacterial infection.

lipl-3 is an ortholog of members of the human Lipases family including LIPF; lipl-3 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, acting on ester bonds, based on protein domain information; lipl-3 is localized to the lysosome.

ugt-42 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-42 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

icl-1 encodes a predicted isocitrate lyase/malate synthase, an enzyme known to function in the glyoxylate cycle; ICL-1 was identified in a screen for proteins that interact with GEX-3, a homolog of human HEM-2 which is required for embryonic development; ICL-1 appears to act downstream of DAF-16 to influence lifespan.

tank-1 (formerly known as pme-5) encodes a protein containing N-terminal ankyrin repeats and C-terminal poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase (PARP) regulatory and catalytic domains that is orthologous to human tankyrase 1 (TNKS; OMIM:603303) and tankyrase 2 (TNKS2; OMIM: 607128), but structurally more similar to the ADPRT-3 tankyrase of Dictyostelium discoideum; TANK-1 also contains a lysine-rich region, a WGR domain, which may mediate DNA interaction, and a coil-coiled region; X-ray-induced apoptosis of germ cells is slightly increased in tank-1(RNAi) animals; DNA damage via ionizing radiation induces tank-1 expression, and this induction absolutely requires HUS-1; TANK-1 is ubiquitously expressed throughout the life cycle, including in the germ line, and localizes to the nucleus.

ges-1 encodes a gut-specific type B carboxylesterase; by homology, GES-1 hydrolyzes carboxylic ester substrates to yield an alcohol and a carboxylic anion, however, loss of GES-1 activity via mutation or RNAi does not result in any obvious abnormalities; GES-1 is expressed solely in the intestinal, or E, lineage from the 4 E-cell stage of gut development through adulthood; GES-1 contains a C-terminal endoplasmic reticulum (ER) retention sequence, KDEL, which suggests that it localizes to the ER lumen; GES-1 expression in the gut appears to be positively regulated by ELT-2, a gut-specific GATA-type transcription factor expressed throughout the C. elegans life cycle and essential for normal gut development.

alh-2 is an ortholog of human ALDH1B1 (aldehyde dehydrogenase 1 family member B1), RP11-162P23.2 and ALDH2 (aldehyde dehydrogenase 2 family (mitochondrial)); alh-2 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information.

alh-5 is an ortholog of members of the human ALDH (Aldehyde dehydrogenases) family including ALDH3B2; alh-5 is predicted to have aldehyde dehydrogenase [NAD(P)+] activity, based on protein domain information.

RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that F59A7.7 is affected by csr-1, bar-1, mir-34, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, tax-6, and isp-1; microarray studies indicate that F59A7.7 is affected by Methylmercuric chloride, Atrazine, and Paraquat; tiling array and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F59A7.7 is enriched in the coelomocytes and germ line.

cysl-4 is an ortholog of human Cbs (cystathionine-beta-synthase); tiling array, microarray, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that cysl-4 is affected by hpl-2, nhr-114, bar-1, prg-1, csr-1, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, mdt-15, npr-1, jmjd-3.1, mir-34, aak-2, tax-6, and isp-1; microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that cysl-4 is affected by Methylmercuric chloride, Tunicamycin, Manganese chloride, D-glucopyranose, D-glucose, Diazinon, Paraquat, and Colistin; RNA sequencing studies indicate that cysl-4 is enriched in the germ line and male.

ckb-4 encodes an isoform of choline kinase whose activity has been verified in vitro, and that has a strong preference for choline over ethanolamine; CKB-1 through CKB-4 comprise a related group ('B') of choline kinases.
C01B4.6 is an ortholog of human GALM (galactose mutarotase); C01B4.6 is predicted to have carbohydrate binding activity and catalytic activity, based on protein domain information.

Y45G12C.3 is an ortholog of human GSTP1 (glutathione S-transferase pi 1); microarray, tiling array, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that Y45G12C.3 is affected by clk-1, cyc-1, ets-4, lin-15B, age-1, rsr-2, pgrn-1, daf-16, mir-34, elli-1, and lin-22; microarray studies indicate that Y45G12C.3 is affected by Progesterone; microarray studies indicate that Y45G12C.3 is enriched in the pharynx, intestine, and hermaphrodite-specific tissues.

ndx-2 encodes a NUDIX hydrolase; by sequence comparison, NDX-2 is predicted to be orthologous to human NUDT5 which, in vitro, possesses ADP-sugar diphosphatase activity; in C. elegans, loss of ndx-2 activity via RNA-mediated interference (RNAi) does not result in any obvious abnormalities, consistent with the proposed nonessential roles for Nudix proteins in eliminating potentially toxic nucleotide metabolites from cells and modulating levels of metabolic intermediates by shuttling them into alternative biochemical pathways.
nuo-5 is orthologous to human NADH-UBIQUINONE OXIDOREDUCTASE Fe-S PROTEIN 1 (NDUFS1; OMIM:157655), which when mutated leads to mitochondrial complex I deficiency.
Y45G12B.3 is an ortholog of human L2HGDH (L-2-hydroxyglutarate dehydrogenase); Y45G12B.3 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-53 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-53 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
acs-21 is an ortholog of human ACSF3 (acyl-CoA synthetase family member 3); acs-21 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information.

tat-6 encodes one of six C. elegans subfamily IV P-type ATPase that, by sequence similarity, is proposed to function as an aminophospholipid translocase (flippase); tat-6, which appears to be expressed at very low levels, is 73% identical to the highly expressed tat-5 gene, suggesting that it is a recent duplication of tat-5; animals homozygous for a tat-6 deletion allele, ok1984, are reportedly viable.
gst-23 is an ortholog of human GSTP1 (glutathione S-transferase pi 1); gst-23 is predicted to have glutathione transferase activity, based on protein domain information.

scrm-3 encodes a putative phospholipid scramblase homologous to human PLSCR1-5, and paralogous to other C. elegans SCRMs (e.g., SCRM-1); SCRM-3 is expressed in neurons, anal depressor muscle, and occasionally in body wall muscle cells; however, in apoptotic germline cells, SCRM-3 is fully dispensable for normally rapid engulfment and largely dispensable for phosphatidylserine exposure; SCRM-3 does not bind WAH-1 in vitro, and scrm-3(tm631) mutants have no obvious phenotype.

T20D4.7 is an ortholog of human NXNL1 (nucleoredoxin-like 1) and NXNL2 (nucleoredoxin-like 2); microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that T20D4.7 is affected by Aldicarb, Multi-walled carbon nanotubes, and Diazinon; tiling array and RNA sequencing studies indicate that T20D4.7 is enriched in the body wall muscle cell, hypodermis, Z4, Z1, and muscle cell.

ugt-64 is an ortholog of members of the human UGT (UDP glucuronosyltransferases) family including UGT8; ugt-64 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

cysl-3 is an ortholog of human Cbs (cystathionine-beta-synthase); cysl-3 is involved in cysteine biosynthetic process from serine; cysl-3 is predicted to have cysteine synthase activity, based on protein domain information.
R08F11.1 is an ortholog of human GBA2 (glucosylceramidase beta 2); R08F11.1 is predicted to have glucosylceramidase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-32 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-32 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

cyp-35A5 encodes one of over 80 C. elegans cytochrome P450s, NADPH-dependent monooxygenases that metabolize endogenous and exogenous compounds; RT-PCR experiments indicate that cyp-35A5 mRNA is upregulated in response to treatment with  xenobiotics, such as PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) or PAHs (polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons); loss of cyp-35A/C gene family activity in the presence of xenobiotics can diminish the reproductive decline seen in wild-type worms treated with the same  compounds; in addition, cyp-35A(RNAi) also results in a reduction of fat content.

cyp-35A4 encodes one of over 80 C. elegans cytochrome P450s, NADPH-dependent monooxygenases that metabolize endogenous and exogenous compounds; loss of cyp-35A/C gene family activity in the presence of xenobiotics can diminish the reproductive  decline seen in wild-type worms treated with the same compounds; in addition, cyp-35A(RNAi) also results in a reduction of fat content.

Category 2: Transcription: general machinery: RNA Pol I
Category 3: Transcription: general machinery: RNA Pol I: subunit
Description: rpac-40 is an ortholog of human POLR1C (RNA polymerase I subunit C); rpac-40 is predicted to have DNA-directed 5'-3' RNA polymerase activity and protein dimerization activity, based on protein domain information.
D2063.1 is localized to the striated muscle dense body.

hpo-18 is an ortholog of human ATP5EP2 (ATP synthase, H+ transporting, mitochondrial F1 complex, epsilon subunit pseudogene 2) and ATP5E (ATP synthase, H+ transporting, mitochondrial F1 complex, epsilon subunit); hpo-18 is predicted to have proton-transporting ATP synthase activity, rotational mechanism, based on protein domain information.

F32D1.5 is an ortholog of human GMPR (guanosine monophosphate reductase) and GMPR2 (guanosine monophosphate reductase 2); F32D1.5 is predicted to have GMP reductase activity, based on protein domain information.
T08H10.1 is an ortholog of members of the human AKR (Aldo-keto reductases) family including AKR1C1; T08H10.1 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-61 is an ortholog of members of the human UGT (UDP glucuronosyltransferases) family including UGT3A2; ugt-61 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information; ugt-61 is expressed in the pharynx, tail, intestine, and the excretory cell.

adss-1 is an ortholog of human ADSSL1 (adenylosuccinate synthase like 1) and AdSS (adenylosuccinate synthase); adss-1 is predicted to have GTP binding activity and adenylosuccinate synthase activity, based on protein domain information; adss-1 is expressed in the pharynx, anal depressor muscle, hypodermis, nervous system, reproductive system, intestine, and the body wall musculature.

hsp-6 is an ortholog of human HSPA9 (heat shock protein family A (Hsp70) member 9)\; hsp-6 is involved in mitochondrial unfolded protein response\; hsp-6 is predicted to have ATP binding activity and unfolded protein binding activity, based on protein domain information\; hsp-6 is expressed in the muscle cell and the intestine\; hsp-6 is localized to the mitochondrion.

ugt-9 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-9 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information; ugt-9 is expressed in the pharyngeal cell.

T19H12.6 is an ortholog of human GGT2 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 2), GGT5 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 5) and GGT1 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 1); T19H12.6 is predicted to have glutathione hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-12 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-12 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-11 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-11 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-13 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-13 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-14 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-14 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-8 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-8 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information; ugt-8 is expressed in the pharynx, nervous system, intestine, and the excretory cell.

H23N18.4 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); H23N18.4 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

catp-2 is an ortholog of members of the human ATPase H+/K+ transporting family including ATP12A and ATP1 (ATPase Na+/K+ transporting subunits) family including ATP1A1; catp-2 is predicted to have nucleotide binding activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-7 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-7 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-63 is an ortholog of members of the human UGT (UDP glucuronosyltransferases) family including UGT8; ugt-63 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information; ugt-63 is expressed in the muscle cell and the hypodermis.

ugt-51 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-51 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
C03A7.13 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

Category 2: Unknown: Stress response: regulated by multiple stresses
Category 3: Unknown: Stress response: regulated by multiple stresses
Description: RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that C52A10.2 is affected by Ethanol, Tryptophan, Mianserin, Bisphenol A, Bisphenol S, 4-bromodiphenyl ether, Fluoranthene, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, R24, single-walled carbon nanotubes, Colistin, Allantoin, Sirolimus, and Triclosan; tiling array studies indicate that C52A10.2 is enriched in the intestine.

natc-2 encodes the C. elegans ortholog of N-alpha-acetyltransferase 30, the catalytic subunit of the N-alpha-acetyltransferase complex (NAT complex); NATC-2 is predicted to function in a NAT complex with NATC-1 to catalyze transfer of the acetyl group of Acetyl-CoA to the alpha-amino group of the N-terminal methionine of substrate proteins; natc-2(RNAi) enhances the dauer formation phenotype of daf-2 mutant animals, suggesting that NATC-2 activity is necessary to inhibit dauer formation.

acl-6 encodes a mitochondrial glycerol-3-phosphate acyltransferase; acl-6 is predicted to play a role in triacylglycerol biosynthesis, and acl-6 expression is upregulated in animals during dauer larval development in response to direct exposure to daumone.
cox-16 is an ortholog of human PTRH2 (peptidyl-tRNA hydrolase 2); cox-16 is predicted to have aminoacyl-tRNA hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-48 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-48 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
hex-2 encodes a beta-N-acetylhexosaminidase.
gcst-1 is orthologous to the human gene GLYCINE CLEAVAGE SYSTEM T-PROTEIN (AMT; OMIM:238310), which when mutated leads to glycine encephalopathy.
F25B4.6 is orthologous to the human gene 3-HYDROXY-3-METHYLGLUTARYL COA SYNTHASE (HMGCS2; OMIM:600234), which when mutated leads to disease.

C53A3.2 is an ortholog of human PDXP (pyridoxal phosphatase) and PGP (phosphoglycolate phosphatase); C53A3.2 is predicted to have phosphatase activity, based on protein domain information; C53A3.2 is expressed in the hypodermis and the intestine.

F44E7.2 is an ortholog of human PDXP (pyridoxal phosphatase) and PGP (phosphoglycolate phosphatase); F44E7.2 is predicted to have phosphatase activity, based on protein domain information; F44E7.2 is expressed in the mu_int_R, mu_int_L, hypodermis, and the nervous system.

galt-1 encodes a galactosyltransferase that is a member of a novel glycosyltransferase family of proteins found in a wide variety of multicellular eukaryotes, but not in mammals; when expressed in insect calls, GALT-1 demonstrates manganese-dependent galactosyltransferase activity; loss of galt-1 activity results in animals that are resistant to the toxic effects of the fungal galectin CGL2 from the ink cap mushroom Coprinopsis cinerea.
dhs-16 encodes a short-chain dehydrogenase predicted to be mitochondrial.

Category 3: Signaling: heteromeric G protein: adenylyl cyclase
Description: acy-2 encodes an adenylyl cyclase; an intragenic deletion of acy-2 is lethal at the first larval stage of development; the terminal phenotype resembles that seen in loss-of-function gsa-1 mutants.

mcp-1 encodes a GDP-D-glucose phosphorylase with similarity to the human protein encoded by C15orf58 and Arabidopsis VTC2; when expressed in vitro, MCP-1 exhibits GDP-D-glucose phosphorylase activity and animals lacking mcp-1 activity accumulate GDP-D-glucose; an MCP-1::GFP reporter fusion protein is expressed in embryos and larvae in neurons, the spermatheca, and the anterior hypodermis and localizes to the cytoplasm.
dhs-17 encodes a member of the short-chain dehydrogenases/reductases family (SDR).
fil-2 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information; fil-2 is expressed in the intestine.

Category 2: Unknown: Stress response: regulated by multiple stresses
Category 3: Unknown: Stress response: regulated by multiple stresses
Description: Microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F13H6.3 is affected by cyc-1, csr-1, glp-1, cox-5B, hsf-1, mir-34, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, emb-4, alg-1, tdp-1, daf-2, and daf-16; microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F13H6.3 is affected by Tryptophan, 1-methylnicotinamide, Mianserin, Bisphenol A, Bisphenol S, 4-bromodiphenyl ether, Cadmium, Fluoranthene, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, Albendazole, Cry5B, Quercetin, Humic substances, R24, Paraquat, Multi-walled carbon nanotubes, Sirolimus, and Ag nanoparticles; microarray, tiling array, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F13H6.3 is enriched in the intestine and in the PVD, OLL, and AFD neurons.

RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that F13H6.4 is affected by npr-1, ifg-1, dpy-21, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, lin-22, smg-2, eri-1, and ain-1; microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F13H6.4 is affected by Methylmercuric chloride, Tunicamycin, 4-bromodiphenyl ether, Zidovudine, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, Colistin, and Sirolimus.

acl-8 is an ortholog of human LCLAT1 (lysocardiolipin acyltransferase 1); acl-8 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring acyl groups, based on protein domain information; acl-8 is expressed in the pharynx, anal depressor muscle, nervous system, reproductive system, intestine, and the body wall musculature.
The T05H4.4 gene encodes a homolog of the human gene CYB5R3, which encodes a cytochrome b5 reductase.
The T05H4.5 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene NADH-CYTOCHROME B5 REDUCTASE (DIA1), which when mutated leads to methemoglobinemia (OMIM:250800).
T05H4.7 is predicted to have chitinase activity, based on protein domain information.
acl-9 is an ortholog of human LCLAT1 (lysocardiolipin acyltransferase 1); acl-9 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring acyl groups, based on protein domain information.

W01A11.1 is an ortholog of human EPHX1 (epoxide hydrolase 1); W01A11.1 is predicted to have cis-stilbene-oxide hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information; W01A11.1 is expressed in the pharynx, nervous system, reproductive system, pharyngeal-intestinal valve, intestine, anal sphincter muscle, and the body wall musculature.

dgtr-1 encodes an acyl chain transfer enzyme; dgtr-1 is required for formation of the eggshell permeability barrier, a distinct envelope that forms between the embryonic plasma membrane and the trilaminar eggshell.

Microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that moc-2 is affected by cyc-1, jmjd-1.2, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, fog-2, emb-4, fbf-1, nuo-6, and lin-35; microarray studies indicate that moc-2 is affected by Ethosuximide, Sirolimus, and Cholesterol; tiling array, RNA sequencing, and microarray studies indicate that moc-2 is enriched in the hypodermis and in neurons including the dopaminergic, PVD, OLL, and AFD neurons.

acs-1 is an ortholog of human ACSF2 (acyl-CoA synthetase family member 2); acs-1 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information; acs-1 is expressed in the nervous system, intestine, and the somatic gonad.
mdh-1 encodes a malate dehydrogenase; by homology, MDH-1 is predicted to function to reversibly catalyze the formation of oxaloacetate from malate.

lipl-4 encodes a triglyceride lipase; by homology, LIPL-4 is predicted to function in lipid hydrolysis; genetic studies indicate that lipl-4 functions as part of an endocrine signaling pathway that coordinates reproductive status, fat metabolism, and longevity; in response to reduced insulin signaling or germline removal (glp-1 mutant animals), lipl-4 expression is induced in the intestine, in a DAF-16-dependent manner; overexpression of lipl-4 can extend lifespan, in a manner dependent upon autophagy genes, such as bec-1, vps-34, and lgg-1.

K04A8.10 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that K04A8.10 is affected by cyc-1, daf-16, ubc-9, jmjd-3.1, hsf-1, dpy-21, mir-34, smg-2, his-3, sir-2.1, and ahr-1; microarray studies indicate that K04A8.10 is affected by Tryptophan, Methylmercuric chloride, Ethanol, Resveratrol, Chlorpyrifos, Diazinon, Colistin, and Sirolimus.

ppt-1 encodes the C. elegans palmitoyl protein thioesterase-1 ortholog; by homology PPT-1 is predicted to function in degradation of palmitoylated proteins and ppt-1 mutations result in loss of enzymatic activity from mixed-stage extracts; in C. elegans, ppt-1 activity is essential for mitochondrial organization and biogenesis in neuronal and muscle cells, as well as for proper timing of the onset of both the L4-to-adult molt and egg laying; ppt-1 is also required for normal egg-laying behavior and for a fully normal adult

W02F12.2 is an ortholog of human ACER1 (alkaline ceramidase 1) and ACER2 (alkaline ceramidase 2); W02F12.2 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, acting on carbon-nitrogen (but not peptide) bonds, in linear amides, based on protein domain information.

dlst-1 is an ortholog of human DLST (dihydrolipoamide S-succinyltransferase); dlst-1 is predicted to have dihydrolipoyllysine-residue succinyltransferase activity, based on protein domain information.

hpo-8 is an ortholog of human HACD2 (3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydratase 2) and HACD1 (3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydratase 1); microarray, proteomic, and RNA sequencing studies indicate that hpo-8 is affected by sma-2, gld-1, let-7, set-25, met-2, mir-34, daf-12, dpy-21, hrde-1, and emb-4; microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that hpo-8 is affected by Mercuric Chloride, Rotenone, Progesterone, Colistin, Allantoin, and Sirolimus; sage analysis, tiling array, and microarray studies indicate that hpo-8 is enriched in the intestine and male-specific tissues.
C55H1.1 is expressed in the nervous system.

mys-1 encodes a MYST family histone acetyltransferase orthologous to Drosophila EG0007.7, human TIP60, and S. cerevisiae Esa1p; during vulval development, mys-1 acts as Class C synMuv gene:  mys-1 mutations enhance mutations in components of the C. elegans NuRD and Rb repressor complexes that negatively regulate expression of genes required for vulval induction; in addition, mys-1(RNAi) enhances mutations in pha-4, which encodes a FoxA transcription factor required for pharyngeal organogenesis; mys-1 mutations also cause a synthetic slow growth phenotype in combination with mutations in the MCD-1 zinc-finger protein; thus, mys-1 activity is essential for proper cell fate specification of different cell types at different times during C. elegans development.
lmd-5 is predicted to have chitin binding activity, based on protein domain information.

ugt-39 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-39 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-40 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-40 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-37 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-37 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-38 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-38 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

fat-7 encodes an essential delta-9 fatty acid desaturase that is required for the synthesis of monounsaturated fatty acids; fat-7 can substitute for the functions of the other two fatty acid desaturases, fat-5 and fat-6; RNA interference has shown that fat-7 is required for viability and normal growth.

ugt-41 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-41 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

ugt-36 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-36 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

F09G2.8 is an ortholog of human PLD4 (phospholipase D family member 4), PLD5 (phospholipase D family member 5) and PLD3 (phospholipase D family member 3); F09G2.8 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information; F09G2.8 is expressed in the pharynx, nervous system, tail, intestine, arcade cell, and the rectal gland cell.

C05C8.7 is an ortholog of human MPI (mannose phosphate isomerase); C05C8.7 is predicted to have mannose-6-phosphate isomerase activity and zinc ion binding activity, based on protein domain information; C05C8.7 is expressed in the seam cell.
lmd-4 is predicted to have chitin binding activity, based on protein domain information.

cyp-35A1 encodes one of over 80 C. elegans cytochrome P450s, NADPH-dependent monooxygenases that metabolize endogenous and exogenous compounds; RT-PCR experiments indicate that cyp-35A1 mRNA is upregulated in response to treatment with xenobiotics,  such as PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) or PAHs (polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons); loss of cyp-35A/C gene family activity in the presence of xenobiotics can diminish the reproductive decline seen in wild-type worms treated with the same compounds; in addition, cyp-35A(RNAi) also results in a reduction of fat content.

cyp-35A2 encodes one of over 80 C. elegans cytochrome P450s, NADPH-dependent monooxygenases that metabolize endogenous and exogenous compounds; RT-PCR experiments indicate that cyp-35A2 mRNA is upregulated in response to treatment with xenobiotics, such as PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) or PAHs (polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons); loss of cyp-35A/C gene family activity in the presence of xenobiotics can diminish the reproductive decline seen in wild-type worms treated with the same compounds; in addition, cyp-35A(RNAi) also results in a reduction of fat content; cyp-35A2 reporter gene fusions are strongly expressed in the intestine following treatment with xenobiotics.

gst-41 is an ortholog of human GSTP1 (glutathione S-transferase pi 1); RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that gst-41 is affected by Rotenone, Bisphenol A, Quercetin, Humic substances, and single-walled carbon nanotubes; tiling array studies indicate that gst-41 is enriched in the hypodermis and in the dopaminergic neurons.

ftn-1 encodes one of two C. elegans ferritin heavy chain homologs; ftn-1 activity is essential for normal lifespan under iron stress conditions and, in addition, has been reported to be essential for embryogenesis; an ftn-1::gfp reporter is expressed in the intestine at all stages of development and its expression, as well as that of ftn-1 mRNA, increases under iron stress conditions and in the background of mutations in the second ferritin-encoding gene, ftn-2.

cyp-32A1 is an ortholog of human CYP19A1 (cytochrome P450 family 19 subfamily A member 1) and CYP4V2 (cytochrome P450 family 4 subfamily V member 2); cyp-32A1 is predicted to have heme binding activity, iron ion binding activity, and oxidoreductase activity, acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen, based on protein domain information.

lpb-4 encodes a homolog of the novel fatty acid binding protein, As-p18, found in the parasitic nematode Ascaris suum; As-p18 is a member of a family of small intracellular fatty acid binding proteins (iFABPs); unlike most lpb family members lpb-4 lacks a secretory signal
F26D11.1 is an ortholog of human IDNK (IDNK, gluconokinase); F26D11.1 is predicted to have kinase activity, based on protein domain information.
ech-3 is expressed in the intestine.

sptl-2 is an ortholog of human SPTLC3 (serine palmitoyltransferase long chain base subunit 3) and SPTLC2 (serine palmitoyltransferase long chain base subunit 2); sptl-2 is predicted to have catalytic activity and pyridoxal phosphate binding activity, based on protein domain information.
vrs-1 encodes a predicted valyl-tRNA synthetase that affects embryonic viability, growth, and morphology

vha-18 encodes an an ortholog of subunit H of the cytoplasmic (V1) domain of vacuolar proton-translocating ATPase (V-ATPase); VHA-18 and VHA-15 are co-orthologs; VHA-18 is a predicted cytosolic stator (stalk) component.

stdh-4 encodes a putative steroid dehydrogenase expressed in larval and  adult pharynx; STDH-4 is orthologous to human HSD17B3 (OMIM:605573,  mutated in pseudohermaphroditism), HSD17B12 (OMIM:609574), and HSDL1,  and paralogous to LET-767 and STDH-1/-3; STDH-4 has no obvious function  in mass RNAi assays.
asns-1 encodes a predicted asparagine synthase (glutamine-hydrolysing); ASNA-1 is predicted to catalyze the synthesis of L-asparagine from L-aspartate.

F41E6.5 is an ortholog of human HAO2 (hydroxyacid oxidase 2) and HAO1 (hydroxyacid oxidase 1); F41E6.5 is predicted to have FMN binding activity and oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information; F41E6.5 is expressed in the pharynx and the intestine.

H14N18.4 is an ortholog of human GGT5 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 5), GGT2 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 2) and GGT1 (gamma-glutamyltransferase 1); H14N18.4 is predicted to have glutathione hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information.
tag-38 is an ortholog of human SGPL1 (sphingosine-1-phosphate lyase 1); tag-38 is predicted to have carboxy-lyase activity, based on protein domain information.

spas-1 is an ortholog of human SPAST (spastin); spas-1 is involved in microtubule depolymerization, microtubule severing, oogenesis, protein homooligomerization and vulval development; spas-1 exhibits microtubule binding activity and microtubule-severing ATPase activity; epidermal expression of SPAS-1 triggers mild effects on embryonic elongation, which are dramatically enhanced by let-502 weak loss of function; spas-1 is expressed throughout the body including the gonad, intestine, and the vulva; spas-1 is localized to the cytoskeleton and the perinuclear region of cytoplasm.

K07B1.4 is an ortholog of members of the human DGAT2 (Diacylglycerol O-acyltransferase 2) family including DGAT2; K07B1.4 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring acyl groups other than amino-acyl groups, based on protein domain information; K07B1.4 is expressed in the intestine, rectal gland cell, and the body wall musculature.

acl-14 is an ortholog of human LPGAT1 (lysophosphatidylglycerol acyltransferase 1); acl-14 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring acyl groups, based on protein domain information; acl-14 is expressed in the pharynx, head, tail, reproductive system, intestine, and the body wall musculature.
haao-1 is an ortholog of human HAAO (3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase); haao-1 is predicted to have iron ion binding activity, based on protein domain information.

pfk-1.2 encodes a 6-phosphofructokinase (E.C. 2.7.1.11), paralogous to PFK-1.1; pfk-1.2 is required for fertility, full body size, and normally rapid growth in mass RNAi assays; pfk-1.2 transcripts are enriched during spermatogenesis.

cyp-29A4 is an ortholog of human CYP19A1 (cytochrome P450 family 19 subfamily A member 1) and CYP4V2 (cytochrome P450 family 4 subfamily V member 2); cyp-29A4 is predicted to have heme binding activity, iron ion binding activity, and oxidoreductase activity, acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen, based on protein domain information.
lipl-2 is an ortholog of members of the human Lipases family including LIPF; lipl-2 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, acting on ester bonds, based on protein domain information.

Category 3: Neuronal function: synaptic function: neurotransmitter metabolism
Description: anmt-3 is an ortholog of human INMT-FAM188B (INMT-FAM188B readthrough (NMD candidate)) and members of the Seven-beta-strand methyltransferase motif containing family including NNMT; anmt-3 is predicted to have methyltransferase activity, based on protein domain information; anmt-3 is expressed in the pharyngeal muscle cell and the body wall musculature.

uda-1 is an ortholog of human ENTPD5 (ectonucleoside triphosphate diphosphohydrolase 5) and ENTPD6 (ectonucleoside triphosphate diphosphohydrolase 6 (putative)); uda-1 is involved in GDP metabolic process and UDP metabolic process; uda-1 exhibits guanosine-diphosphatase activity and uridine-diphosphatase activity; uda-1 is localized to the cytoplasmic vesicle membrane.

T06E8.1 is orthologous to the human gene 1-ACYLGLYCEROL-3-PHOSPHATE O-ACYLTRANSFERASE 2 (LYSOPHOSPHATIDIC ACID ACYLTRANSFERASE, BETA) (AGPAT2; OMIM:603100), which when mutated leads to disease; T06E8.1 protein is predicted to be mitochondrial.

R04B5.6 encodes one of two C. elegans sorbitol dehydrogense orthologs; by homology the product of R04B5.6 is predicted to catalyze the reversible oxidation of sorbitol to fructose in the presence of NAD+; in the embryo, an R04B5.6::gfp fusion is expressed in pharyngeal cells and head neurons.

ugt-47 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-47 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

Category 2: Transcription: general machinery: RNA Pol III
Category 3: Transcription: general machinery: RNA Pol III
Description: rpc-25 is an ortholog of human POLR3H (RNA polymerase III subunit H); rpc-25 is predicted to have DNA-directed 5'-3' RNA polymerase activity, based on protein domain information.

gna-1 encodes one of two C. elegans glucosamine 6-phosphate N-acetyltransferases (GNAs); by homology, GNA-1 is predicted to be required for the formation of UDP-N-acetylglucosamine, a substrate in chitin synthesis, Golgi and cytoplasmic glycosylation, and GPI anchoring; gna-1, like chs-2, is expressed pharyngeally rather than in germline, and (unlike its paralog gna-2) does not have an osmotically-sensitive embryonic lethal RNAi phenotype; as loss of gna-1 activity via large-scale RNAi screens does not result in any obvious abnormalities, the precise role of GNA-1 in C. elegans development and/or behavior is not yet known.
B0024.13 is an ortholog of human SRD5A3 (steroid 5 alpha-reductase 3); B0024.13 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, acting on the CH-CH group of donors, based on protein domain information.

ceeh-2 encodes a soluble epoxide hydrolase (sEH) orthologous to human  ABHD7 and ABHD9; recombinant CEEH-2 is biochemically active in vitro on  epoxyeicosatrienoic acids and leukotoxins (EpOMEs); conversely, CEEH-2  is inhibited by urea-based antagonists of mammalian sEH that elevate  EpOME levels when fed to C. elegans; perhaps because of genetic  redundancy with its paralog CEEH-1, CEEH-2 has no obvious function in  mass RNAi assays.

ugt-1 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-1 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

pap-1 encodes a poly (A) polymerase; large-scale RNAi screens indicate that PAP-1 activity is essential for reproduction, embryonic and larval development, proper body morphology, normal rates of growth, and coordinated locomotion.
The ndx-4 gene encodes a homodimeric diadenosine tetraphosphate (Ap(4)A) hydrolase that belongs to the NUDIX hydrolase family.

ugt-33 is an ortholog of human UGT3A2 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A2) and UGT3A1 (UDP glycosyltransferase family 3 member A1); ugt-33 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.

Category 3: Neuronal function: synaptic function: neurotransmitter metabolism
Description: cat-4 is an ortholog of human GCH1 (GTP cyclohydrolase 1); cat-4 is involved in dopamine biosynthetic process from tyrosine, melanin biosynthetic process and tetrahydrobiopterin biosynthetic process; cat-4 exhibits GTP cyclohydrolase I activity; cat-4 is expressed in the muscle cell, certain pharyngeal motor neurons, B cell, Y cell, certain interneurons, certain amphid neurons, hyp7 syncytium, intestinal cell, body wall musculature, dopaminergic neurons, serotonergic neurons, and certain mechanosensory neurons.
T21C9.6 is predicted to have ATP binding activity and kinase activity, based on protein domain information.
H27A22.1 is an ortholog of human QPCTL (glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase like) and QPCT (glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase); H27A22.1 is expressed in the pharynx, hypodermis, head, and the tail.

sqv-4 encodes a UDP-glucose 6-dehydrogenase, biochemically active in vitro, that is required for cytokinesis of one-cell embryos and for vulval morphogenesis; SQV-4 is orthologous to Drosophila SUGARLESS, human UGDH (OMIM:603370), and zebrafish JEKYLL; SQV-4 is expressed in many cell types, notably oocytes and uterine, seam, pharyngeal, and spermathecal cells, with expression being prominent in 14 of the 22 vulval nuclei of late L4 larvae; the common requirement for SQV-4 in both cytokinesis and morphogenesis may be to promote filling an extracellular space with hygroscopic proteoglycans (either in the eggshell, or underneath the L4 cuticle), which in turn may cause the space to fill with fluid.

ugt-34 encodes a putative UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT), belonging to a large nematode-specific expanded family of UGTs, that inhibits CEP-1- and HUS-1-dependent germline apoptosis as do BMK-1, RAD-50, and RAD-51.

D1054.1 is an ortholog of human PNPLA4 (patatin like phospholipase domain containing 4); D1054.1 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, based on protein domain information; D1054.1 is expressed in the reproductive system.

secs-1 is an ortholog of human SEPSECS (Sep (O-phosphoserine) tRNA:Sec (selenocysteine) tRNA synthase); secs-1 exhibits identical protein binding activity and is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring selenium-containing groups, based on protein domain information; secs-1 is expressed in the ventral nerve cord and the head neurons.
dhs-18 encodes a predicted short-chain dehydrogenase.

atp-5 is an ortholog of human ATP5H (ATP synthase, H+ transporting, mitochondrial Fo complex subunit D); atp-5 is predicted to have hydrogen ion transmembrane transporter activity, based on protein domain information.

cyp-29A2 is an ortholog of human CYP19A1 (cytochrome P450 family 19 subfamily A member 1) and CYP4V2 (cytochrome P450 family 4 subfamily V member 2); cyp-29A2 is predicted to have heme binding activity, iron ion binding activity, and oxidoreductase activity, acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen, based on protein domain information; cyp-29A2 is expressed in the pharynx, hypodermis, nervous system, intestine, and the body wall musculature.
The T19B10.3 gene encodes an ortholog of the human gene GALACTOSIDASE, BETA 1 (GLB1), which when mutated leads to gangliosidosis type I (OMIM:230500).

gly-20 encodes an N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase II (GnTII); by homology, GLY-20 is predicted to function in the Golgi to effect protein N-glycosylation; expression of C. elegans GLY-20 and bovine beta1,4-galactosyltransferase I in a baculoviral insect cell system results in efficient glycosylation of mammalian proteins.
dhs-19 encodes a short-chain dehydrogenase predicted to be mitochondrial.
dhs-20 encodes a short-chain dehydrogenase predicted to be mitochondrial.

Category 3: Signaling: heteromeric G protein: guanylyl cyclase
Description: daf-11 encodes a transmembrane guanylate cyclase; daf-11 activity is required for a number of processes dependent upon normal chemosensory function, including dauer formation and recovery and chemotaxis to both volatile and non-volatile odorants; daf-11 is also required for axon formation; daf-11 acts together with daf-21 to regulate chemosensory function and genetically upstream of daf-12 with respect to dauer larvae formation; in addition, daf-11 positively regulates expression of daf-28 and daf-7, which encode insulin and TGF-beta signaling molecules, respectively; a DAF-11::GFP fusion protein is expressed in a subset of amphid neurons where it localizes to the ciliated sensory endings, the cell soma, and the dendrites.

bus-18 encodes a lysocardiolipin acyltransferase; bus-18 is required for colonization by Microbacterium nematophilum and the tail-swelling response to M. nematophilum  infection, as well as for cuticle integrity, traction during movement,  full body size, normally rapid growth, and vulval morphogenesis; bus-18  is also needed for normal cuticle antigens and resistance to emetine or  colchicine, perhaps because its cuticle is abnormally permeable.

pyc-1 encodes the C. elegans pyruvate carboxylase ortholog; by homology, PYC-1 is predicted to function as a key regulatory enzyme of gluconeogenesis, lipogenesis, and anaplerosis, localizing to the mitochondrial matrix and catalyzing the formation of oxaloacetate from pyruvate and carbonate; pyc-1 expression is induced upon exposure of C. elegans to cadmium.

mpst-1 is an ortholog of human tst (thiosulfate sulfurtransferase) and MPST (mercaptopyruvate sulfurtransferase); microarray studies indicate that mpst-1 is affected by Resveratrol, Cry5B, Humic substances, Sirolimus, and Allantoin; tiling array, RNA sequencing, and microarray studies indicate that mpst-1 is enriched in the body wall muscle cell, germ line, intestine, and muscle cell.

pho-8 is an ortholog of human ACPT (acid phosphatase, testicular), ACPP (acid phosphatase, prostate) and ACP2 (acid phosphatase 2, lysosomal); microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that pho-8 is affected by Heme, 1-methylnicotinamide, Rotenone, Tunicamycin, Lactoferrin, Resveratrol, Chlorpyrifos, Humic substances, Copper sulfate, Paraquat, Colistin, and Sirolimus; RNA sequencing studies indicate that pho-8 is enriched in neurons.
sodh-1 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information; sodh-1 is expressed in the muscle cell, hypodermis, nervous system, and the intestine.
sodh-2 is predicted to have oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information.
F58H1.3 is an ortholog of human ENOPH1 (enolase-phosphatase 1); F58H1.3 is predicted to have acireductone synthase activity and magnesium ion binding activity, based on protein domain information.

mans-2 is an ortholog of human MAN1A1 (mannosidase, alpha1A, member 1), MAN1C1 (mannosidase, alpha1C, member 1) and MAN1A2 (mannosidase, alpha1A, member 2); mans-2 has a calcium ion dependent mannosyl-oligosaccharide 1,2-alpha-mannosidase activity, based on enzymatic assay, with Man6GlcNAc2 as a final product.

Category 3: Signaling: heteromeric G protein: guanylyl cyclase
Description: gcy-33 encodes a soluble guanylate cyclase beta subunit; GCY-33 activity is required in the ciliated BAG head sensory neurons to sense decreases in O2 levels and effect corresponding behavioral changes; a gcy-33::GFP reporter is expressed in the BAG neurons; biochemical characterization of chimeric molecules containing the GCY-33 N-terminal H-NOX domain fused to the rat beta1 guanylate cyclase indicate that the GCY-33 H-NOX domain can form complexes with NO, CO, and O2 and that binding can positively regulate catalytic activity of the molecule.

F10C2.4 encodes a homolog of the DNA polymerase delta complex subunit A that is required in embryos for the normal timing of embryonic cell divisions (much as DIV-1 is) and, also, for normal chromosome segregation (probably because of defective DNA replication).
kmo-1 is an ortholog of human KMO (kynurenine 3-monooxygenase); kmo-1 is predicted to have FAD binding activity and oxidoreductase activity, based on protein domain information.
R07B7.8 is an ortholog of human PLB1 (phospholipase B1); R07B7.8 is predicted to have hydrolase activity, acting on ester bonds, based on protein domain information.
C27A7.1 is orthologous to the human gene NPPASE (ENPP1; OMIM:173335), which when mutated leads to disease.

C27A7.3 is an ortholog of human ENPP1 (ectonucleotide pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase 1), ENPP2 (ectonucleotide pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase 2) and ENPP3 (ectonucleotide pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase 3); C27A7.3 is predicted to have catalytic activity, based on protein domain information.
C27A7.5 is an ortholog of human ASPG (asparaginase); C27A7.5 is predicted to have asparaginase activity, based on protein domain information.
ugt-55 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information.
ugt-56 is predicted to have transferase activity, transferring hexosyl groups, based on protein domain information; ugt-56 is expressed in the nervous system.

Microarray and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F55C5.2 is affected by Methylmercuric chloride, Manganese chloride, D-glucose, Levamisole, Zidovudine, Fluoranthene, Quercetin, Paraquat, Colistin, adsorbable organic bromine compounds, and Sirolimus; tiling array and RNA sequencing studies indicate that F55C5.2 is enriched in the coelomocytes, germ line, and male.

R04F11.2 is an ortholog of human ATP5I (ATP synthase, H+ transporting, mitochondrial Fo complex subunit E); R04F11.2 is predicted to have hydrogen ion transmembrane transporter activity, based on protein domain information.

R04F11.3 is an ortholog of human POLD3 (DNA polymerase delta 3, accessory subunit); microarray, RNA sequencing, and tiling array studies indicate that R04F11.3 is affected by cyc-1, isp-1, age-1, aak-2, daf-12, tatn-1, fog-3, hsf-1, elli-1, pgl-1, pgl-3, glh-4, glh-1, emb-4, sir-2.1, fbf-1, gld-1, and let-60; RNA sequencing and microarray studies indicate that R04F11.3 is affected by Rotenone, Manganese chloride, D-glucose, Testosterone, Atrazine, Cadmium, Hydrolyzable Tannins, single-walled carbon nanotubes, and Sirolimus; tiling array and RNA sequencing studies indicate that R04F11.3 is enriched in the germ line and in neurons including the AVA and dopaminergic neurons.
